SIMPLE: huddle
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Huddle
<hw>Hud"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Huddled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Huddling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. OE.
<ets>hoderen</ets>, <ets>hodren</ets>, to cover, keep, warm; perh. akin
to OE. <ets>huden</ets>, <ets>hiden</ets>, to hide, E. <ets>hide</ets>,
and orig. meaning, to get together for protection in a safe place. Cf.
<er>Hide</er> to conceal.]</ety> <def>To press together promiscuously,
from confusion, apprehension, or the like; to crowd together confusedly;
to press or hurry in disorder; to crowd.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The cattle <qex>huddle</qex>d on the lea.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Huddling</qex> together on the public square . . . like a
herd of panic-struck deer.</q> <rj><qau>Prescott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Huddle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Huddle
<hw>Hud"dle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To crowd (things)
together to mingle confusedly; to assemble without order or
system.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our adversary, <qex>huddling</qex> several suppositions together,
. . . makes a medley and confusion.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To do, make, or put, in haste or roughly; hence, to
do imperfectly; -- usually with a following preposition or adverb;
<as>as, to <ex>huddle on</ex>; to <ex>huddle up</ex>; to <ex>huddle
together</ex>.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Huddle</xex> up a peace.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>J. H. Newman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let him forescat his work with timely care,⟦br⟧
Which else is <qex>huddled</qex> when the skies are fair.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now, in all haste, they <qex>huddle</qex> on⟦br⟧
Their hoods, their cloaks, and get them gone.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Huddle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Huddle
<hw>Hud"dle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A crowd; a number of persons or
things crowded together in a confused manner; tumult; confusion.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>huddle</xex> of ideas.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Huddler</ent>⟦br⟧
